FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - INDIA (07): (ANDHRA PRADESH) BOVINE, SPREAD, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*******************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 17 Oct 2013
Source: The Hindu [edited]
http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/fmd-outbreak-worries-animal-husbandry-officials/article5243382.ece


The outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) among cattle, even vaccinated animals, has been worrying the officials of the animal husbandry department.

According to sources, at least 4 FMD cases have been reported in the State [Andhra Pradesh] including one animal affected with the disease at the Frozen Semen Bull Station in Karimnagar. The rest were reported at a research centre in Nandyal of Kurnool district, Tirupati zoo [Chittoor district], and a private dairy in Ranga Reddy district.

The animals in South India are being usually vaccinated for O-type virus in addition to 3 other types -- C, A, and Asia 1 [see comment below]. The vaccination is being conducted twice a year with a 6 month gap following the strict protocols. FMD is one of the World Organisation for Animal Health's (OIE) listed diseases.

Continuous rain in the State in the recent past is being attributed as one of the causes of the outbreak of FMD in the incidents mentioned above. "Food, fodder, and water contamination may be one of the reasons for the outbreak. Though, not many animals were affected with FMD, we treat it as an outbreak. This was reported to national animal disease testing laboratories and we are waiting for their report," Dr Dasyam Venkateswarlu, Commissioner and Director, Animal Husbandry told The Hindu.

Stating that crossbred animals are susceptible to FMD, Mr Venkateswarlu said that this would be proven economically disastrous for the farmers as the animals would be crippled and milk yield would be reduced. More than 2000 animals reportedly died due to FMD in Karnataka in recent past.

[Byline: R Avadhani]

